post_text:
IMPORTANT Meal Update: Effective tomorrow, Wednesday, September 2, meal pickup and delivery will be free for ALL students through December 31! Multi-day meals are available for pick up at most schools (and delivery in many communities) on Mondays and Wednesdays between 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. Children picking up meals do not need identification. Parents/ guardians should bring a student ID or most recent report card to support the number of meals requested.

Due to the Labor Day holiday, the Wednesday, Sept. 2 meal distribution will consist of meals for Wednesday, Thursday, Friday and Tuesday, September 8th. The regular distribution schedule will resume on Wednesday, Sept. 9th.

Please visit our website for more info and a list of delivery locations by city.
https://www.pgcps.org/reopen/distance-learning/#Meals

post_text:
PGCPS parents Rahman A. Culver and Halima Aziza discuss their family's experiences in this Washington Post op-ed.

"Prince George‚Äôs County is still home to many educational institutions that regularly foster Black excellence. Our children have had the privilege to attend several of these public institutions ‚Äî including Montessori, language immersion recognized by the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs and National Blue Ribbon STEM programs. ... Contrary to our experiences, our children have had the reaffirming opportunity to excel in educational environments where large numbers of people who look like them thrive alongside their White, Asian and Latinx peers."

post_text:
Statement from Dr. Alvin Thornton, Board of Education Chair, on #ReopenPGCPS

"Prince George‚Äôs County Public Schools is committed to the health, safety and wellbeing of all students and educators. We have listened to parents and our community in making decisions that prioritize our students‚Äô needs. At this time, we have no plans to change course in reopening PGCPS. The 2020-21 school year will start with distance learning as scheduled Monday, Aug. 31. We will work with the County Executive, local health officials and the CEO to assess when it is safe for our students and employees to resume in-person learning."

THECLARICE.UMD.EDU
K12 New Music Project | The Clarice Smith Performing Arts Center

National Orchestral Institute
August 13 at 1:06 PM ¬∑

The National Orchestral Institute + Festival has pledged to amplify creative voices that have been unfairly silenced in the orchestral ecosystem due to systemic racism. Today, we're thrilled to announce the expansion of our K-12 New Music Project! In partnership with NOI+F Sphinx Fellow Camille Jones, Prince George's County Public Schools, the DC Youth Orchestra Program and Hawaii Youth Symphony, we will commission eight Black, Indigenous and people of color composers to write works that will increase representation in K-12 orchestral music.

We give special thanks to the League of American Orchestras for awarding NOI+F with a $30,000 Futures Fund grant to make this project possible!

Read Full Announcement ‚Üí go.umd.edu/noifk12

post_text: Check out this award-winning Maryland History Day documentary on voting rights by former Accokeek Academy student Jacqueline Dianis, featuring an interview with the late Congressman John Lewis.
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
IMG 00871

Maryland History Day
July 20 at 12:22 PM ¬∑

We honor the legacy of Congressman John Lewis, who passed away Friday night. Over the weekend, we were contacted by a former History Day parent who shared with us her daughter's 2014 Documentary on Voting Rights, which included an interview with the late Congressman.

In the video, Lewis says: "We risked our lives for voting rights because we thought the vote was powerful, that it was important. The right to vote, the right to participate in the democratic process, is precious. It‚Äôs almost sacred. It‚Äôs the most powerful nonviolent tool that we have in a democratic society. You can be low income, you can be middle class, you can be a billionaire, but we all have one vote. And why did people want to keep us from voting? Because it‚Äôs powerful."

Students throughout the National History Day program continue to research Lewis' life and analyze his many writings to learn about the long fight for voting rights.

View the documentary here: https://bit.ly/2CPlU6b

post_text:
We extend our warmest wishes and gratitude to retiring Principal Cecelia Jones-Bowlding who has been an anchor in the Glenarden Woods Elementary School community and our school system! Jones-Bowlding most recently led the school to being recognized as a 2019 U.S. Department of Education National Blue Ribbon School and a Maryland Blue Ribbon School!

"I am #PGCPSProud of a journey that taught me to never give up when serving teachers, students and parents. The rewards are unimaginable, for I was educated and employed by a system that reached down and in some cases provided the boots I had to wear. Humbled and honored."

Introducing our 2020 Teacher of the Year, Cooper Lane Elementary School third-grade teacher Mary Piccirilli! The announcement was made today on a video call with finalists and a surprise visit to Piccirilli‚Äôs home.

Piccirilli will compete statewide for Maryland Teacher of the Year, coordinated by the Maryland State Department of Education. As county Teacher of the Year, she will receive a pre-paid three-year lease on a new 2020 Honda from sponsor Pohanka Honda.

‚ÄúMs. Piccirilli truly represents what I consider to be a model teacher,‚Äù said CEO Dr. Monica Goldson. ‚ÄúNot only does she possess the skills to engage students and effectively teach the curriculum, she truly cares about equity, academic success and the overall well-being of all students.‚Äù

IN THE NEWS | Port Towns Elementary School teacher Ariana Tabaku raised $1,300 to buy 20 tablets for families in need!

"She set them up with the right apps for each student and drove her Toyota Scion around Prince George's County on the weekends, dropping them off at their homes."

"One child went to hug me for a tablet," Tabaku said. "I had to tell him I can't."

post_text:
CEO Dr. Monica Goldson penned an op-ed in the Washington Post, urging Congress to include funding for broadband access in the future COVID-19 relief packages.

PGCPS, like many school districts, quickly moved to a distance learning model. But too many students and families do not have access to the tools necessary to complete lessons and assignments, engage in discussion, and keep pace with other students. This inequity is part of a larger ‚Äúdigital divide‚Äù that affects roughly 12 million children across the country.

Dr. Goldson‚Äôs call to action comes as we have initiated programs with local and business partners to provide Chromebooks and WiFi hotspots for students. Without widespread federal assistance, this inequity will persist and children will fall behind.
shared_text:
WASHINGTONPOST.COM
Opinion | End the digital divide. Our children are being left behind.

This inequity is part of a larger ‚Äúdigital divide‚Äù that affects roughly 12 million children across the country.

Dr. Goldson‚Äôs call to action comes as we have initiated programs with local and business partners to provide Chromebooks and WiFi hotspots for students. Without widespread federal assistance, this inequity will persist and children will fall behind.

PGCPS will continue learning from home through May 15 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19). Info is forthcoming on how our school year will continue.

We're working to ensure all students continue to have access to learning at home and resources including: online lessons, PreK-5 instructional programming via PGCPS-TV, school wifi hotspots and enrichment packets available both online and at meal distribution sites.

Student meal pick-up will continue on Mondays and Wednesdays.

We began this school year #PGCPSProud and together, we will move forward #PGCPSStrong ‚Äî even if from a distance.

For more information and updates, please visit https://www.pgcps.org/coronavirus/

post_text:
A message from the Northwestern High School Community on the passing of professional school counselor and coach Terrance Burke>>> Mr. Terrance Burke was a Professional School Counselor at Northwestern High School for 15 years. During his time there, he positively impacted many lives by being a consummate professional, strong advocate for students and an endearing colleague.

Mr Burke changed the lives of everyone he touched. He was a strong advocate and mentor to his students and their parents, and he treated colleagues and friends like family. He was dedicated to helping and being of service. He was definitely one of a kind and will be truly missed.

Our school community is a continuous chain and we are now missing a link. Our hearts are broken at the loss of our colleague, friend, coach and professional school counselor. He touched the lives of many by his words of encouragement, helping hand and sincere heart. Our prayers for comfort go out to his family, colleagues and friends during this difficult time.

shared_text:
Governor Larry Hogan
March 12 at 8:00 PM ¬∑

Today I announced a series of major actions to protect public health and safety and limit the spread of the COVID-19 pandemic in Maryland. A comprehensive list can be found here: https://governor.maryland.gov/2020/03/12/governor-hogan-announces-major-actions-to-protect-public-health-limit-spread-of-covid-19-pandemic/

My first and highest priority is protecting the health, the safety, and the welfare of the people of Maryland. We are all in this together, and we cannot stop the spread of this virus without each and every one of you doing your part. But I want you all to know that we will get through this together. Our state has already faced and overcome daunting challenges before, and we will do so again.

County Executive Angela Alsobrooks
March 6 at 2:19 PM ¬∑

As you may have heard, Maryland now has 3 confirmed cases of the novel coronavirus, COVID-19. All 3 cases are in Montgomery County and are individuals who recently traveled outside of the country. We are monitoring the situation in our County and across the State. We are in contact with State and federal public health partners, receiving consistent and regular updates. Our Emergency Operations Center and Joint Information Center remain activated at an enhanced level to respond to the evolving situation, which allows us to continue taking the appropriate steps to keep Prince Georgians safe and healthy. We ask residents to stay informed with the latest updates by visiting our dedicated coronavirus website: https://www.princegeorgescountymd.gov/3397/Coronavirus
